{:id "war-machine/dynamic-over-static"
 :claim "A dynamic display that animates state changes over time reveals patterns that a static snapshot hides — trends, rhythms, decay, and momentum become visible as motion."
 :ground "The futon2 ant war is animated tick by tick. Watching it for ten seconds tells you which colony is winning, which foraging strategy is working, and where the front line is moving. A single screenshot of the same simulation — a static snapshot — shows positions but not momentum. You cannot tell from a screenshot whether a colony is growing or dying. The same applies to the strategic state: a static report says '85% stack commits' but does not show whether that percentage is rising, falling, or stable over weeks."
 :warrant "Temporal patterns (acceleration, deceleration, periodicity, sudden change) are perceptible in animation but invisible in snapshots. A fever chart shows whether the patient is getting better or worse; a single temperature reading does not. For strategic awareness, the trajectory matters more than the position — you need to see the movie, not just the frame."
 :backing "The ant war proves this: two colonies can have identical cell counts at tick 100, but one is expanding and the other is collapsing. Only the animation reveals which. The war room equivalent: two repos can have the same commit count this week, but one has accelerating activity and the other has decaying activity. Replaying the last 14 days as an animation makes the difference obvious."
 :qualifier "Animation adds complexity — replay controls, speed settings, visual noise from rapid changes. The display must be pausable and steppable, not just a movie. The static fallback (markdown report) remains necessary for precise reference."
 :rebuttal "Animation can be distracting — motion draws attention to the most visually active area, which may not be the most strategically important. The layout must ensure that important-but-quiet areas (e.g., a sorry that's not receiving any attention) are visually salient even when nothing is moving there."
 :tension "Static reports show position but not momentum; the operator cannot distinguish growth from decay, acceleration from stagnation."
 :resolution "Animate the strategic state over time. Replay days as ticks. Position shows state; motion shows trajectory. Combine with spatial layout so that both where things are and where they're going are visible simultaneously."}
